<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 7; Column 2; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
169 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLATFORM; 
</P>
<P>
INDEPENDENT FUND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Retired Judge BRUCE SUMNER, former presiding judge of Orange County Superior 
Court, is chairman of the National Committee to Preserve Social Security and 
Medicare. He told The Times: 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The first thing that we found is that our members and seniors generally are 
very concerned with the fact that Social Security is considered in 
budget-deficit calculations. There is a very large reserve in the Social 
Security Trust Fund, and this reserve is loaned to the government to finance 
the programs that have been carried on in the last 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
And that money, of course, will have to be repaid. The problem is further 
compounded by the fact that in determining what the deficit is in the budget, 
the amount of that reserve is deducted from the actual deficit. This gives a 
very unrealistic result. 
</P>
<P>
Social Security should be as it was originally, namely an independent agency -- 
independent of the Congress and independent of the President. Since Social 
Security is unique, it's a social insurance program that's paid for by the 
people that are members. And as I have indicated, the program is in surplus; it 
has a large reserve and so it doesn't require any money from the general 
taxpayer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070990-0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 244663 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 9, 1990, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 7; Column 5; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
748 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN RIGHT; 
</P>
<P>
AMERICA IS FREE TO GO HOME; 
</P>
<P>
A SOVIET-GERMAN MARRIAGE OF CONVENIENCE LEAVES LITTLE ROOM FOR U.S. ROLE IN 
EUROPE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANE KIRKPATRICK, Jeane Kirkpatrick writes a syndicated column in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From the time he was appointed general secretary of the Soviet Communist Party, 
Mikhail S. Gorbachev has had three principal goals vis-a-vis the West: to 
prevent the resurgence of a German threat in the heart of Europe, to break the 
Soviet Union out of its technological and economic isolation and to eliminate a 
major U.S. presence in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
If Gorbachev stays in power, he has a good chance of achieving all three in 
this current season of change and reconfiguration in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
For such success -- if he achieves it -- he will be beholden not only to his 
own undoubted ability but, above all, to the extraordinary diplomatic skill and 
activity of West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and his foreign minister, 
Hans-Dietrich Genscher. For their trouble, they will also have achieved a 
united, sovereign Germany and left the Soviets, the French and the Americans 
each feeling that the country whose interest most closely coincides with their 
own is Germany. 
</P>
<P>
It promises to be a stunning achievement for both Gorbachev and Kohl. 
</P>
<P>
Soviet officials have made no secret of their fear of resurgent German power. 
What a surprise, then, to hear Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze say, 
as he did a few months ago, that the security of Europe is better served by the 
reunification of Germany than by its division, providing that it takes place in 
the context of an appropriate pan-European settlement. 
</P>
<P>
The European settlement that Gorbachev has had in mind is one that would 
"overcome" the division of Europe into blocs and hostile alliances; would 
integrate the Soviet Union and the East into a common European family; would 
give the Soviet economy access to Western technology and financial assistance 
and, of course, would almost as a byproduct eliminate a significant U.S. role 
in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
It is not wholly clear at what point Gorbachev realized, as Shevardnadze put 
it, "it is necessary to utilize in depth the potential of a German-Soviet 
economic cooperation." By the time the Soviets understood that the Germans 
could help solve their economic problems, the Germans had already understood 
that there would be no reunification without Soviet support. A marriage of 
convenience was negotiated that promises to help both partners achieve their 
hearts' desires. 
</P>
<P>
Kohl and Genscher made themselves representatives of increased Soviet inclusion 
in international arenas. In addition, Bonn offered financial assistance highly 
favorable to Moscow. It guaranteed a $3 billion credit for the Soviet Union and 
agreed that East Germany would pay approximately $750 million toward the cost 
of supporting 360,000 Soviet troops and their families in East Germany in the 
last six months of 1990, providing Moscow hard currency at a highly subsidized 
rate. 
</P>
<P>
Now Kohl, with French President Francois Mitterrand, has sponsored a proposal 
for $15 billion in Western aid to the Soviets. Next week, Kohl will travel to 
Moscow to report to Gorbachev on progress so far and to appeal for the Soviets 
to drop opposition to German membership in NATO -- which the United States and 
Western Europeans want as their price for supporting German reunification. 
</P>
<P>
But the Soviets' price is likely to be high and some of its terms may be 
ultimately incompatible with meaningful German membership in a meaningful NATO. 
</P>
<P>
Mitterrand has been a willing and active participant in the Gorbachev-Kohl 
policy. His own quasi-Gaullist vision of a stable Europe without the blocs 
coincides with Gorbachev's in some crucial ways. They also share a barely 
articulated desire to reduce the role of the United States and NATO in Europe 
and to enhance the Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
Like Gorbachev, Mitterrand looks toward a Europe for the Europeans. 
</P>
<P>
The desired American contribution to the Gorbachev-Kohl design is now clear -- 
it is for economic aid and a "flexible" policy toward NATO. Where the Bush 
Administration will come out is not yet clear. My own sense is that a 
meaningful long-term role for NATO will not survive the current reconfiguration 
of Europe -- if present trends in the Soviet Union continue -- and that Bush 
cannot join Kohl and Mitterrand in a major financial aid program when the 
Soviets are still spending nearly 20% of their gross national product on the 
military. 
</P>
<P>
But a "no" will not matter that much to the emergence of the new Europe. 
</P>
<P>
Europe is once again absorbed with itself, creating its own complex 
correlations of power. And America is free to go home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
