<HEADLINE>
<P>
THREE'S COMPANY LO-TECH DANCE SERIES IS OFF TO A FAST-PACED START 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EILEEN SONDAK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Three's Company launched its Lo-Tec Series with three drop-dead dances by an 
innovative pair of modernists to anchor the program. Add to that, the striking 
presence of the most arresting performers seen on this summer dance series in 
recent memory, and you have an opening concert that will be a hard act to 
follow. 
</P>
<P>
Lar Lubovitch principal Nancy Colahan was the featured attraction, and she 
stole the show with two stunning solos from modern dance pioneer Jane Dudley's 
retrospective concert. 
</P>
<P>
Dudley (one-time Martha Graham soloist) is one of the unsung heroes of modern 
dance. Fortunately, Colahan's beautifully-realized re-creations of "Harmonica 
Breakdown," the choreographer's brilliant signature piece, and "Cante 
Flamenco," a fiery, flamenco-inspired work dedicated to the great Spanish 
dancer La Passionara, gave San Diego dance buffs an opportunity to see some of 
the groundbreaking work Dudley did back in the 1930s and '40s. 
</P>
<P>
Colahan was electrifying in the highly-theatrical dances, despite the low level 
of technical support available at the Hillcrest studio. And her splendid 
costumes (authentically reproduced from Dudley's marvelous originals) enhanced 
the effect. 
</P>
<P>
The choppy robotics and angular leg lifts of "Harmonica Breakdown" contrasted 
sharply with the flamboyant port de bras and defiant backbends of Dudley's 
flamenco-style dance. Seen together, they left little doubt about Dudley's 
capacity for invention or her keen choreographic eye. 
</P>
<P>
Although Colahan has danced in San Diego before (as a member of the acclaimed 
Lubovitch troupe), it took this lo-tec appearance to highlight her powerful 
stage magic. Let's hope Three's Company gets her back for an encore next year. 
</P>
<P>
The Lo-Tec concerts also showcased a contemporary classic, "Three Tangos," 
choreographed in 1985 by the late Jack Moore. This staging, danced by a trio of 
Three's Company summer interns, was set by New York-based dancer Lance 
Westergard. 
</P>
<P>
The inventive triptych of solos was cleverly juxtaposed against a musical 
pastiche that underscored "Tango's" parody with refreshing wit. Nicely danced 
by the well-drilled performers, it got the concert off to a running start 
Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
Colahan's husband, Lonne Moretton, was on hand for the kick-off concert -- but 
only as choreographer. 
</P>
<P>
Moretton created "In Flight" especially for the five local dancers. And they 
executed the ebullient airborne moves with admirable assurance, their student 
status notwithstanding. 
</P>
<P>
Two of the interns were invited to dance their own designs. Vicki Tolleson 
(one-time Merce Cunningham dancer) performed "Some Rhythm, No Reason," which 
more or less lived up to its name. Gail Olsen came up with "Breeze," a vigorous 
solo that kept her jumping along the lines of a jazzy score. 
</P>
<P>
Long-limbed Tonnie Haig snared the spotlight in Westergard's "Leaves of 
Hypnos," an evocative dance that took its cues from the piano plucks of a score 
by David Koblitz, and showed how far she has come in a short while. 
</P>
<P>
The Lo-Tec series will continue to occupy Three's Company's Hillcrest studio at 
8:30 Saturday and Sunday nights through mid-September. 
</P>
<P>
If the rest of the series comes close to upholding last weekend's standards, it 
will provide quite a summer bounty for local aficionados. 
</P>
</TEXT>
