<HEADLINE>
<P>
WIFE TELLS OF APARTHEID FOE'S AFFAIR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, South Africa 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The wife of mixed-race anti-apartheid cleric Allan Boesak said their marriage 
had ended because he was having an affair with a white journalist, newspapers 
reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
"This time he has gone too far. . . . Our marriage is over," Dorothy Boesak 
told the Sunday Times. 
</P>
<P>
Allan Boesak, 44, a friend of Nobel Prize winner Archbishop Desmond Tutu and 
the president of the Geneva-based World Alliance of Reformed Churches, has 
admitted to having an affair with television journalist Elna Botha, niece of 
former Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha, newspapers said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
The papers said Boesak and Botha, who is married to a television news anchor, 
were seen at a Cape Town hotel where they had spent four days together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
CLERGY; MARRIAGES; BOESAK, ALLAN 
</P>
