<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOHN STILL LOVES THE GAME, BUT HIS FAMILY COMES FIRST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVEN HERBERT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his first full season away from professional baseball, Tommy John has become 
a self-described full-time father and husband. This spring he and his wife, 
Sally, managed a New Jersey Little League team that sons Travis and Tommy 
played for. 
</P>
<P>
John has also made motivational speeches to corporate groups and served as a 
sports consultant to a New York City hotel. However, he would like to return to 
major league baseball in some capacity. 
</P>
<P>
"The Dodgers have approached me on a couple of minor league assignments, but I 
have to put my family first," said John, who pitched for six teams, including 
the Dodgers and the Angels during a 26-year major league career. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm looking into doing television baseball work, but only 30 to 40 games a 
season, so I would have a chance to talk about the game I love and know a lot 
about, and yet still have a family life. That's more important than anything." 
STEVEN HERBERT 
</P>
</TEXT>
