<HEADLINE>
<P>
ICE CARVER HAS A NO-SWEAT JOB; 
</P>
<P>
ART: JAMES LUFF SPENDS SUMMER DAYS HOLED UP IN A WALK-IN FREEZER SCULPTING 
PARTY CENTERPIECES FROM A MATERIAL MORE COMMONLY SEEN IN PARTY DRINKS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATT LAIT, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COSTA MESA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the mercury crept into the 80s one day last week, James Luff bundled up in a 
heavy jacket, rain pants, two pairs of gloves and insulated boots to perform 
what may be Orange County's coolest summer job: ice sculpting. 
</P>
<P>
"It's definitely a way to escape the heat," said Luff, who has been a 
professional ice sculptor for the past 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
While others flocked to the beaches to bask in the summer sun, Luff closed 
himself inside his freezer-studio and went to work on a 300-pound ice cube. 
</P>
<P>
As the temperature hovered at 16 degrees, Luff first used a lightweight chain 
saw to gently outline the figure he wanted to sculpt. ("I can look at (a block 
of ice) and see what I want to carve inside it," Luff said.) 
</P>
<P>
Then with sweeping strokes of the saw, he chopped away large chunks of ice, and 
a pair of wings and the long neck of a swan soon began to emerge. Gradually, 
the swipes of the saw gave way to precision strokes as Luff defined the slope 
of the breast, the curve of the neck. 
</P>
<P>
For the final touches, Luff employed a pruning saw and a large fork to smooth 
away the rough edges and detail the feathers of his three-foot-tall swan. After 
several hours of work -- and one or two breaks outdoors to warm his hands and 
feet -- Luff's latest creation was ready to stand as the sparkling centerpiece 
to a party, where it would immediately begin to melt away. 
</P>
<P>
Luff professes not to mind the ephemeral nature of his art. "I don't feel bad 
seeing it melt. I enjoy watching the people's reactions, the oohs and aahs . . 
. ," he said. "It's like cooking a good meal for someone. They enjoy it. Then 
it's gone." 
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Luff has been dabbling in wood carvings recently. "It would be 
nice to have something a little more permanent," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Luff, 37, is one of few ice sculptors to make his own ice. 
</P>
<P>
Most carvers buy their ice from manufacturers who typically use a freezing 
system that produces blocks with a cloudy white core. 
</P>
<P>
Luff utilizes a specially designed system that creates blocks of ice as clear 
as crystal. 
</P>
<P>
"It takes three days to make a block of ice, but it's worth the wait," said 
Luff, who also sells his 40-inch-by-20-inch-by-10-inch blocks to other ice 
sculptors. 
</P>
<P>
Luff said he got hooked on ice carving when he was working as a cook in 
Vancouver, Wash., and saw a chef carving a block of ice for a buffet-table 
centerpiece. "He showed me the tools . . . how to use them and told me to go to 
it," he said. "That was my first lesson. After that, I knew ice carving was 
what I wanted to do." 
</P>
<P>
His works have graced the tables of parties, movie sets, business functions and 
wedding receptions. He created the swan centerpiece in "Beverly Hills Cop" and 
the mermaid in "Dragnet." He even sculpted a pair of lungs that were featured 
on the cover of a medical journal. 
</P>
<P>
By far the largest sculpture he has ever done was a replica of the Egyptian 
Sphinx that required 90 blocks of ice. The entire project cost about $18,000. 
</P>
<P>
In an average month, Luff carves between 30 and 40 sculptures. Most sell for a 
couple hundred dollars to several thousand dollars, depending on their 
complexity and size. 
</P>
<P>
After completing his swan last week, Luff looked outside at the midday sun and 
admitted that the frigid environs of his studio are not always the place to be 
in summer. 
</P>
<P>
"Getting away from the heat is nice, but it also would be nice to enjoy the 
sunny days sometimes," he said with a smile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, Ice sculptor James Luff of Costa Mesa wields a power drill to 
hone the features of a swan he is carving in his 16-degree studio. DON TORMEY / 
Los Angeles Times; Photo, COLOR, A jagged knife is used to add finishing 
touches to James Luff's swan creation, which will serve as the centerpiece to a 
party. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
