</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
STERLING, Mass. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Authorities can't find rhyme or reason to the theft of a statue commemorating 
the little lamb that followed 19th-Century resident Mary Sawyer to school one 
day. 
</P>
<P>
The heist on July 1 has vexed some residents who believe they have been robbed 
of a piece of history. 
</P>
<P>
"I can't understand anybody taking it," said Karen Gaylord, a 20-year resident 
and part-time spokeswoman for the Sterling Police Department. "It has great 
historical value to the town, but it's not something that you could sell." 
</P>
<P>
The concrete statue of the lamb had stood on the town common since the early 
1960s and was a fixture of this central Massachusetts town of 6,000, said Ruth 
Hopfmann of the Sterling Historical Society. 
