<TEXT>
<P>
When country music singer Dan Seals and his wife bought property that included 
a slave cemetery, help came pouring in from those who wanted to clean it up. 
</P>
<P>
"It just evolved into a big thing around those people who were directly 
involved -- us because we live there and the descendants of people that were 
buried there," Seals said. 
</P>
<P>
