<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: TANNING PILL WITH CANTHAXANTHIN MAY DAMAGE VISION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON, AND TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: With all the warnings about the dangers of getting too much sun, I 
was intrigued by an ad I recently saw for a tanning pill. It contains something 
called canthaxanthin which is supposed to be natural, harmless and approved by 
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. 
</P>
<P>
These tanning pills sound too good to be true but they aren't cheap. What do 
you think? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Canthaxanthin is a food coloring that is chemically related to beta 
carotene, the orange color in carrots. The amount of this agent used in food, 
however, is minuscule compared to the levels found in tanning pills. 
</P>
<P>
Such products do not produce a golden glow that resembles a natural tan. The 
skin tends to turn more an orange color, and the stool can turn red. More 
alarming are reports of golden yellow crystals that show up in the retina of 
the eye. Prolonged use of these products may even lead to visual damage. The 
FDA has NOT approved canthaxanthin for use in tanning pills, so these products 
are illegal. If the FDA discovers them being sold, they are seized and removed 
from the market. 
</P>
<P>
You are right to avoid a "natural" tan, but tanning pills don't appear to be 
risk-free either. Another alternative is dihydroxyacetone, a tanning lotion 
found in products such as Clinique Self-Tanning Formula, Coppertone Sunless 
Tanning Lotion and Estee Lauder Self-Action Tanning Creme. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I just picked up a new prescription and the pharmacist told me not to store 
the pills in the bathroom. I like to keep my medications in the medicine chest 
so I remember to take them first thing in the morning. If the lid is on tight, 
what difference does it make where they are stored? 
</P>
<P>
A: Check your bathroom mirror. If it fogs up when you take a shower or bath, 
there is too much humidity in the air to be good for drugs. Child-proof caps 
can't seal that moisture out. And even regular lids let humidity in every time 
the bottle is opened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070990-0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 245332 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 9, 1990, Monday, P.M. Final 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part P; Page 9; Column 1; Late Final Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
116 words 
</P>
